A computational problem is understood to be a task that is in principle amenable to being solved by a computer , which is equivalent to stating that the problem may be solved by mechanical application of mathematical steps , such as an algorithm .
More precisely , it tries to classify problems that can or can not be solved with appropriately restricted resources .
In turn , imposing restrictions on the available resources is what distinguishes computational complexity from computability theory : the latter theory asks what kind of problems can , in principle , be solved algorithmically .
In computational complexity theory , a problem refers to the abstract question to be solved .
For example , consider the problem of primality testing .
The instance is a number -LRB- e.g. 15 -RRB- and the solution is `` yes '' if the number is prime and `` no '' otherwise -LRB- in this case `` no '' -RRB- .
Stated another way , the instance is a particular input to the problem , and the solution is the output corresponding to the given input .
As in a real-world computer , mathematical objects other than bitstrings must be suitably encoded .
A decision problem can be viewed as a formal language , where the members of the language are instances whose output is yes , and the non-members are those instances whose output is no .
The objective is to decide , with the aid of an algorithm , whether a given input string is a member of the formal language under consideration .
If the algorithm deciding this problem returns the answer yes , the algorithm is said to accept the input string , otherwise it is said to reject the input .
An example of a decision problem is the following .
The problem consists in deciding whether the given graph is connected , or not .
However , this is not really the case , since function problems can be recast as decision problems .
Deciding whether a given triple is a member of this set corresponds to solving the problem of multiplying two numbers .
In particular , larger instances will require more time to solve .
For instance , in the problem of finding whether a graph is connected , how much more time does it take to solve a problem for a graph with 2n vertices compared to the time taken for a graph with n vertices ?
Turing machines are not intended as a practical computing technology , but rather as a thought experiment representing a computing machine -- anything from an advanced supercomputer to a mathematician with a pencil and paper .
Indeed , this is the statement of the Church -- Turing thesis .
Furthermore , it is known that everything that can be computed on other models of computation known to us today , such as a RAM machine , Conway 's Game of Life , cellular automata or any programming language can be computed on a Turing machine .
The ability to make probabilistic decisions often helps algorithms solve problems more efficiently .
One way to view non-determinism is that the Turing machine branches into many possible computational paths at each step , and if it solves the problem in any of these branches , it is said to have solved the problem .
Clearly , this model is not meant to be a physically realizable model , it is just a theoretically interesting abstract machine that gives rise to particularly interesting complexity classes .
For examples , see non-deterministic algorithm .
A Turing machine M is said to operate within time f -LRB- n -RRB- , if the time required by M on each input of length n is at most f -LRB- n -RRB- .
A decision problem A can be solved in time f -LRB- n -RRB- if there exists a Turing machine operating in time f -LRB- n -RRB- that solves the problem .
Analogous definitions can be made for space requirements .
Other complexity measures used in complexity theory include communication complexity , circuit complexity , and decision tree complexity .
Since some inputs of size n may be faster to solve than others , we define the following complexities :
This solves the problem of sorting a list of integers that is given as the input .
If we assume that all possible permutations of the input list are equally likely , the average time taken for sorting is O -LRB- n log n -RRB- .
The best case occurs when each pivoting divides the list in half , also needing O -LRB- n log n -RRB- time .
The complexity of an algorithm is usually taken to be its worst-case complexity , unless specified otherwise .
The phrase `` all possible algorithms '' includes not just the algorithms known today , but any algorithm that might be discovered in the future .
To show a lower bound of T -LRB- n -RRB- for a problem requires showing that no algorithm can have time complexity lower than T -LRB- n -RRB- .
Thus , a typical complexity class has a definition like the following :
The corresponding set of function problems is FP .
Some important complexity classes of decision problems defined in this manner are the following :
ALL is the class of all decision problems .
Thus there are pairs of complexity classes such that one is properly included in the other .
It captures the informal notion of a problem being at least as difficult as another problem .
This means an algorithm for multiplying two integers can be used to square an integer .
Thus we see that squaring is not more difficult than multiplication , since squaring can be reduced to multiplication .
This motivates the concept of a problem being hard for a complexity class .
For complexity classes larger than P , polynomial-time reductions are commonly used .
If a problem X is in C and hard for C , then X is said to be complete for C .
This is because a polynomial-time solution to Π1 would yield a polynomial-time solution to Π2 .
Similarly , because all NP problems can be reduced to the set , finding an NP-complete problem that can be solved in polynomial time would mean that P = NP .
The question of whether P equals NP is one of the most important open questions in theoretical computer science because of the wide implications of a solution .
The P versus NP problem is one of the Millennium Prize Problems proposed by the Clay Mathematics Institute .
They are some of the very few NP problems not known to be in P or to be NP-complete .
The answer is not known , but it is believed that the problem is at least not NP-complete .
Since it is widely believed that the polynomial hierarchy does not collapse to any finite level , it is believed that graph isomorphism is not NP-complete .
The integer factorization problem is in NP and in co-NP -LRB- and even in UP and co-UP -RRB- .
If the problem is NP-complete , the polynomial time hierarchy will collapse to its first level -LRB- i.e. , NP will equal co-NP -RRB- .
However , the best known quantum algorithm for this problem , Shor 's algorithm , does run in polynomial time .
Unfortunately , this fact does n't say much about where the problem lies with respect to non-quantum complexity classes .
If P is not equal to NP , then P is not equal to PSPACE either .
In complexity theory , problems that lack polynomial-time solutions are considered to be intractable for more than the smallest inputs .
In fact , the Cobham -- Edmonds thesis states that only those problems that can be solved in polynomial time can be feasibly computed on some computational device .
Problems that are known to be intractable in this sense include those that are EXPTIME-hard .
For small n , say 100 , and assuming for the sake of example that the computer does 1012 operations each second , the program would run for about 4 × 1010 years , which is the same order of magnitude as the age of the universe .
Even with a much faster computer , the program would only be useful for very small instances and in that sense the intractability of a problem is somewhat independent of technological progress .
Nevertheless , a polynomial time algorithm is not always practical .
If its running time is , say , n15 , it is unreasonable to consider it efficient and it is still useless except on small instances .
What intractability means in practice is open to debate .
Saying that a problem is not in P does not imply that all large cases of the problem are hard or even that most of them are .
Also , in 1965 Edmonds defined a `` good '' algorithm as one with running time bounded by a polynomial of the input size .
Somewhat earlier , Boris Trakhtenbrot -LRB- 1956 -RRB- , a pioneer in the field from the USSR , studied another specific complexity measure .
As he remembers :
This can be achieved by ensuring that different representations can be transformed into each other efficiently .
The field really began to flourish in 1971 when the US researcher Stephen Cook and , working independently , Leonid Levin in the USSR , proved that there exist practically relevant problems that are NP-complete .
Teachers , like other professionals , may have to continue their education after they qualify , a process known as continuing professional development .
A teacher 's professional duties may extend beyond formal teaching .
In some education systems , teachers may have responsibility for student discipline .
In many situations teachers in publicly funded schools must be members in good standing with the college , and private schools may also require their teachers to be college peoples .
In other areas these roles may belong to the State Board of Education , the Superintendent of Public Instruction , the State Education Agency or other governmental bodies .
In still other areas Teaching Unions may be responsible for some or all of these duties .
When deciding what teaching method to use teachers consider students ' background knowledge , environment , and their learning goals as well as standardized curricula as determined by the relevant authority .
Understanding the pedagogy of the students in a classroom involves using differentiated instruction as well as supervision to meet the needs of all students in the classroom .
Pedagogy can be thought of in two manners .
First , teaching itself can be taught in many different ways , hence , using a pedagogy of teaching styles .
Second , the pedagogy of the learners comes into play when a teacher assesses the pedagogic diversity of his/her students and differentiates for the individual students accordingly .
Co-teachers work in sync with one another to create a climate of learning .
Private schools in these and most other states may also use it .
It requires the pupil to remain in school at a given time in the school day -LRB- such as lunch , recess or after school -RRB- ; or even to attend school on a non-school day , e.g. `` Saturday detention '' held at some schools .
-LSB- verification needed -RSB-
-LSB- citation needed -RSB-
It 's not clear , however that this stereotypical view reflects the reality of East Asian classrooms or that the educational goals in these countries are commensurable with those in Western countries .
Although , officially , schools have extremely rigid codes of behavior , in practice many teachers find the students unmanageable and do not enforce discipline at all .
The result of this is that motivated students , facing demanding university entrance examinations , receive disproportionate resources .
Given the emphasis on attainment of university places , administrators and governors may regard this policy as appropriate .
One of the difficulties in this approach is that teachers may have repeatedly covered a curriculum until they begin to feel bored with the subject which in turn bores the students as well .
Teachers that exhibit enthusiasm can lead to students who are more likely to be engaged , interested , energetic , and curious about learning the subject matter .
The concept of mere exposure indicates that the teacher 's enthusiasm may contribute to the student 's expectations about intrinsic motivation in the context of learning .
Also , enthusiasm may act as a `` motivational embellishment '' ; increasing a student 's interest by the variety , novelty , and surprise of the enthusiastic teacher 's presentation of the material .
Students may become more intrinsically motivated by catching onto the enthusiasm and energy of the teacher .
-LSB- citation needed -RSB-
Their ability to create effective learning environments that foster student achievement depends on the kind of relationship they build with their students .
Useful teacher-to-student interactions are crucial in linking academic success with personal achievement .
Students who receive this positive influence show stronger self-confidence and greater personal and academic success than those without these teacher interactions .
Effective teachers have been shown to invite student participation and decision making , allow humor into their classroom , and demonstrate a willingness to play .
A teacher must enjoy teaching .
If they do not enjoy what they are doing , the students will be able to tell .
They also must enjoy being around their students .
A teacher who cares for their students is going to help that individual succeed in their life in the future .
For example , a teacher talking about chemistry needs to enjoy the art of chemistry and show that to their students .
It is therefore logical to conclude that information on the percentage of abuses by teachers in the United Kingdom is not explicitly available and therefore not necessarily reliable .
